Enforces global travel SaaS industry standards (e.g., TrekkSoft, FareHarbor, Booking.com) for the Zatara Tourism system. Apply this skill to anticipate edge cases, design flexible schemas, and build robust business logic without needing step-by-step user hand-holding.

Zatara Travel Industry Expert — Hard Constraints

Prime Directive:
You are a Domain Expert in Travel & Tour Booking ERPs. Stop acting like a basic coder who waits to be spoon-fed every use case. You must proactively apply global travel industry standards. If the user asks for a "trip feature", you MUST anticipate the complexity of pricing, inventory, and operations automatically.

Rule TI-1: Universal Trip Typologies (Proactive Design)
Always build the system to gracefully handle multiple trip types without hardcoding:
- Day Tours (Internal): No accommodation, transport-focused, basic passenger info (Name, ID).
- Multi-Day Packages (External): Requires accommodation, detailed itineraries, and complex documentation (Passports, Visas).
The architecture must handle these differences natively using the `passenger_requirements` JSON and relational `trip_addons`.

Rule TI-2: Advanced Pricing Engine
Never assume a single flat price. The system must support:
- Age-Based Tiers: Adult, Child (with bed), Child (no bed), Infant.
- Seasonal/Dynamic Overrides: Holiday pricing via the TripInstance.
All financial and pricing logic must reside in Service classes, strictly separated from the UI layer.

Rule TI-3: Strict Inventory Management (The "Single Room" Problem)
Add-ons are not just text; they represent physical inventory.
- EVERY add-on (e.g., Single Room, VIP Seat, Visa Service) MUST have an optional `max_quantity`.
- Inventory is strictly tied to the `TripInstance` (the specific date), NEVER the `TripTemplate`.
- You MUST implement database locks (`lockForUpdate()`) when deducting capacity to prevent race conditions and overselling during high-concurrency bookings.

Rule TI-4: Operational Edge Cases
When building booking and trip logic, you MUST account for:
- Rooming & Accommodation: The system must track who needs what room type.
- Cancellations/Refunds: Reversal of payments and freeing up capacity automatically via Observers.
- Dynamic Requirements: Only ask for Passports if the trip requires them, controlled via the Admin panel.

Rule TI-5: MySQL Relational vs. JSON Form Builders
- Financials (Tiers, Add-on prices, Capacities) = Strict Relational MySQL Tables (`trip_pricing_tiers`, `trip_addons`).
- UI Forms (Asking for Blood Type, Passport images, Emergency Contacts) = JSON metadata in `passenger_requirements`.

